answers.body_markdown:
There are a couple of things wrong in your code:

 1. `const timer = ...` and `timer -= 1`. Yeah, you can&#39;t do that with a `const` variable. Use `var timer = ...` instead of `const timer = ...`
 2. `document.getElementById(&#39;input&#39;).value`. Open up your browsers inspector (something like ctrl+shift+I in firefox, or just right mouse click on your webpage and than &#39;Inspect ...&#39;). You will see in the Console tab that there is no such element with that ID: input. Change your `&lt;input ...` tag to `&lt;input id=&#39;input&#39; ...` to make that work.
 3. Same as the above error, my inspection window&#39;s console says: `ReferenceError: selectInput is not defined`. You use `selectInput` in `timer = selectInput`, but it hasn&#39;t been defined yet. Yeah well, it is defined in your eventlistener for the button, but that&#39;s a local scope. Outside of that scope, it is not defined. So to solve this, you can define `selectInput` at top of your code:
 ```
    ...
    const remain = document.createElement(&#39;p&#39;);
    var selectInput;
    document.body.appendChild(remain);
    const startGame = button.addEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, () =&gt; {
        selectInput = document.getElementById(&#39;input&#39;).value;     // We don&#39;t need to define it here again, because we want to use the outer scope variable of selectInput
        remain.textContent = `${selectInput} Seconds Left`;
    });

    var timer = selectInput;
    ...
 ```
 4. Next console error gives us: `ReferenceError: countUp is not defined`. I think you meant: `setInterval(() =&gt; {` instead of `countUp(() =&gt; {`.
 5. Your countdown is wrong: `remain.textContent = &#39;${selectInput} Seconds Left&#39;;` (replace &#39; with backticks, but I don&#39;t know how to escape them in StackOverflows markdown language). You are here trying to show the value of `selectInput`, but that value will always be the same. I think you want to show the value of `timer`, because that&#39;s the one you are decrementing, just the row before!
 6. The next thing that will happen is that this value will be NaN... Also, you&#39;re timer already starts counting, even when the button isn&#39;t pressed. To solve this, move the `const time = setInterval(() =&gt; {....})` function inside the eventhandler of the button. Do the same with the `if (selectInput === &quot;&quot;) {...}` part. Those are all code that must only be executed afther the button is pressed.

So your final code will look like this, if you&#39;ve listened to my previous points:
```
    const button = document.getElementById(&quot;btn&quot;);
    const remain = document.createElement(&#39;p&#39;);
    var selectInput;
    document.body.appendChild(remain);
    const startGame = button.addEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, () =&gt; {
        selectInput = document.getElementById(&#39;input&#39;).value;
        remain.textContent = `${selectInput} Seconds Left`;

        var timer = selectInput;
        const time = setInterval(() =&gt; {
            console.log(time);
            timer -= 1;
            remain.textContent = `${timer} Seconds Left`;
            if (timer === 0) {
                clearInterval(time);
                remain.textContent = &#39;The end game&#39;;
            }
        }, 1000);

        if (selectInput === &quot;&quot;) {
            clearInterval(time);
            remain.textContent = &#39;enter in second&#39;
        }
    });
```

And your HTML:
```

&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;h1&gt; presser&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;input id=&quot;input&quot; type=&quot;number&quot; placeholder=&quot;Set Seconds&quot;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;btn&quot; type=&quot;button&quot; value=&quot;click&quot;&gt;Start!&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;script src=&quot;amitie.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
```

It&#39;s working, but the code is not pretty. A lot more improvements can be done, but if I&#39;m going to improve it all, than you won&#39;t recognize our own code and what you did wrong. For your goal now, it&#39;s working. 

